04798nam a22006495i 9780226566795DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017055604  a97802265667957 a10.7208/97802265667952doi  a(DE-B1597)549920  a(OCoLC)1053888266  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aDS119.76b.S7833 2018 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aShulman, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFreedom and Despair :bNotes from the South Hebron Hills /cDavid Shulman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1 On the Usefulness of Despair -- t2 A Taste of South Hebron -- t3 On Wickedness -- t4 Freedom -- t5 Thirst -- t6 Truth, Trust, Conscience -- t7 Final Reflection: On Resistance -- t8 Coda: Iftar at Sarura -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLately, it seems as if we wake up to a new atrocity each day. Every morning is now a ritual of scrolling through our Twitter feeds or scanning our newspapers for the latest updates on fresh horrors around the globe. Despite the countless protests we attend, the phone calls we make, or the streets we march, it sometimes feels like no matter how hard we fight, the relentless crush of injustice will never abate. David Shulman knows intimately what it takes to live your beliefs, to return, day after day, to the struggle, despite knowing you are often more likely to lose than win. Interweaving powerful stories and deep meditations, Freedom and Despair offers vivid firsthand reports from the occupied West Bank in Palestine as seen through the eyes of an experienced Israeli peace activist who has seen the Israeli occupation close up as it impacts on the lives of all Palestinian civilians. Alongside a handful of beautifully written and often shocking tales from the field, Shulman meditates deeply on how to understand the evils around him, what it means to persevere as an activist decade after decade, and what it truly means to be free. The violent realities of the occupation are on full display. We get to know and understand the Palestinian shepherds and farmers and Israeli volunteers who face this situation head-on with nonviolent resistance. Shulman does not hold back on acknowledging the daily struggles that often leave him and his fellow activists full of despair. Inspired by these committed individuals who are not prepared to be silent or passive, Shulman suggests a model for ordinary people everywhere. Anyone prepared to take a risk and fight their oppressive political systems, he argues, can make a difference—if they strive to act with compassion and to keep hope alive. This is the moving story of a man who continues to fight for good in the midst of despair. An indispensable book in our era of reactionary politics and refugee crises, political violence and ecological devastation, Freedom and Despair is a gripping memoir of struggle, activism, and hope for peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-xPeace. 0aPacifistszIsrael. 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyzIsrael. 0aPalestinian ArabszWest BankzHebronxSocial conditions. 0aPeace movementszIsrael. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aIsrael.  aPalestine.  aTa'ayush.  aWest Bank.  adespair.  afreedom.  ahuman rights.  aoccupation.  asettlements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226566795423Coveru